properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Warm, windy, and rainy conditions are expected for the southwest Yukon and northwestern BC beginning tonight. A powerful storm is moving into the Gulf of Alaska tonight. As this system approaches strong southeasterly winds are expected to develop overnight. Areas exposed to winds from the southeast could see gusts to 80 km/h overnight and Tuesday morning. These strong winds will be accompanied by rising temperatures tonight. Precipitation will start as snow and change to rain as temperatures rise above freezing. Periods of rain are expected to continue through Tuesday with the potential for some areas to see 10 to 20 mm through Tuesday afternoon. The warm weather will persist into Wednesday, with temperatures remaining 10 to 20 degrees Celsius above seasonal normals for this time of year. More seasonal conditions will return on Thursday. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm.

properties.Summary:

Additional snowfall amounts of 10 to 20 cm are a possibility Tuesday through Wednesday morning, Strong northerly winds gusting near 70 km/h are also possible tonight and Tuesday, particularly near Lake Huron or Georgian Bay. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Messy week ahead with periods of snow, freezing rain, and rain expected. Total snowfall: 10 to 20 cm. Total rainfall: 10 to 40 mm. Freezing rain duration: 8 to 12 hours. Locations: central Labrador and coastal Labrador from Hopedale and vicinity to Cartwright. Time span: overnight tonight until Thursday afternoon. Remarks: Snow, over western Labrador, will spread to central and coastal Labrador by Tuesday morning. North of Rigolet, the precipitation is expected to remain as snow through Wednesday. From Rigolet to Cartwright and through Upper Lake Melville and Eagle River the snow will change to rain Tuesday afternoon or evening then to a potentially extended and significant period of freezing rain overnight Tuesday night through Wednesday. Eastern areas of Eagle River and coastal areas of Cartwright to Black Tickle may avoid the freezing rain as temperatures should remain just above freezing. All areas should see the precipitation transition to rain Wednesday night into Thursday. The heaviest snowfall rates are expected during the day on Tuesday and the heaviest freezing rainfall rates are expected overnight Tuesday and into Wednesday morning. This wintry mix of snow, freezing rain, and rain is expected to finally end later on Thursday. Snowfall, Freezing Rain, and/or Rainfall Warnings might be needed for some areas in subsequent forecasts. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.

properties.Title: Winter Storm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A major winter storm is expected. 40 to 50 cm of snow followed by 50 to 70 mm of rain is forecast for the Haines Road and South Klondike Highway beginning tonight. A frontal system will move onshore this evening and stall over the region through Wednesday. Snow will begin to fall this evening with strong winds giving blowing snow. 40 to 50 cm of snow is forecast for near White Pass and from Dezadeash Lake to Pleasant Camp. Temperatures will rise to near freezing tonight and remain near freezing through Tuesday. The snow is forecast to change to rain late in the day on Tuesday as the warm airmass pushes through. Significant rainfall is thus forecast Tuesday night through Wednesday with 50 to 70 mm of rain. ### Rapidly accumulating snow will make travel difficult. Road closures are possible. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #YTStorm.

properties.Title: Rainfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A long episode of heavy rain is expected. Maximum rainfall amounts: 80 to 120 mm, except possibly reach 180 mm in the extreme southwestern region of the province. Locations: most of southwestern and central New Brunswick. Time span: this evening through Wednesday morning. Remarks: A slow moving, intense low pressure system over New England will move into Quebec by Wednesday. This system will continue to push rain at times heavy into the province tonight, Tuesday, and Tuesday night before easing off Wednesday morning. At this time, rainfall amounts are expected to be heaviest in the southwestern portion of the province where general rainfall amounts of 80 to 120 mm are expected by Wednesday morning, with some areas potentially reaching near 180 mm. Similar rainfall events in the past have caused road washouts and localized flooding in low-lying areas. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Localized flooding in low-lying areas is possible. Rainfall warnings are issued when significant rainfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 15 to 25 cm is expected. Locations: Labrador City, Wabush, Churchill Falls and vicinity, and Churchill Valley. Time span: tonight and Tuesday. Remarks: The heaviest snow is expected overnight tonight and Tuesday morning. The snow will change to rain Tuesday afternoon over the Churchill Valley region, then to a long and significant period of freezing rain Tuesday night through Wednesday. Further west through Churchill Falls, Labrador City, and Wabush, periods of snow are expected to continue through Tuesday night with an extended and potentially significant period of ice pellets and freezing rain likely on Wednesday. A freezing rain warning is in effect for the Churchill Valley region and might need to be expanded to other regions in subsequent forecasts. ### Rapidly accumulating snow will make travel difficult.
